summary: It amazes me how many youtube videos there are focusing on hypocritical hatred of Brie Larson. I keep seeing videos on the...
body:
It amazes me how many youtube videos there are focusing on hypocritical hatred of Brie Larson. I keep seeing videos on the sidebar that say “CHRIS HEMSWORTH HATES BRIE LARSON!” “CHRIS HEMSWORTH CALLS OUT BRIE LARSON!” and “CHRIS HEMSWORTH SHOCKED AT BRIE LARSON’S STUPID EGO!” as if her comments are anything more than banter between her and her cast mates. 

It’s hypocritical that people are mad that she said Josh Brolin should “be scared” of her (because she’s Captain Marvel) and calling her arrogant when RDJ literally pretends to be a huge diva all the time during events. Just to name a few RDJ moments, “I must be mellowing with age, but the next time I’m not asked the first question..I’m gonna fucking walk out”, him calling out Chris Evans for not going to Paul Rudd’s birthday party randomly during a press interview, RDJ: “We can skip over the dumb parts” Scarlett: “What are the dumb parts?” RDJ: “Oh I don’t know, your character” and those are just a few. 

Another example of this type of behavior happening between cast mates is with Anthony Mackie/Sebastian Stan and Tom Holland. Anthony and Seb constantly call Tom an asshole and say he’s a little brat who needs a juicebox, saying stuff like if they were in the Spider-man movie, it would actually be interesting, etc. This is BANTER! Brie Larson saying things like “Captain Marvel is definitely the strongest” compared to Thor and them going back and forth about it is BANTER. Why is everyone else in the cast allowed to and even praised for making playful yet snide comments to each other, yet the minute Brie Larson does it, it’s time to crucify her for being an arrogant feminazi who wants to burn Marvel to the ground? Like damn, it ain’t that serious yall.

title: Dust Part Two
body:
Part One  Part Three

Hey guys! Here is part two to my Captain Marvel fanfic. Message me if you want to be added to the tag list!

“Carol what the hell is going on?” Maria asked, having just pulled Carol away from the Avengers gathered in the room. 

“Thanks  The Skull and I were fighting his organization from space, but I never saw Thanos. He managed to assemble the most powerful objects in the universe and used them to destroy half the population of every planet. We need to find him.” Carol stood, her shoulders tensed, and all Maria could dow as pull her best friend into a tight hug. 

“You can do it.” Maria whispered, and Carol buried her head into Maria’s neck. 

“Thank you.” She whispered. 

“I don’t mean to interrupt - uh- whatever is going on here.” Clint Barton said, raising his eyebrows, “but we have work to do, and you r family probably should go somewhere safer than a battle group.”

“We aren’t going anywhere.” Monica said, walking away from Nakia, whose weapon she had been examining. 

“She’s right. We may not be superheroes, but we can build planes and fly them pretty damn well if I do say so myself.” Maria added 

“If they are willing to stay, then they stay.” Carol snapped, glaring at Hawkeye.

“Okay!” He said, “but we should probably head over to the others to strategies.”

“Let’s go then.” Carol said, grabbing Maria’s hand and pulling her towards the others, Monica jogging after them. 

“Follow me.” Nakia said, walking towards a circular heavily guarded room. She lead the trio into the room, where Captain America was pacing around, clutching a notebook as he mouthed words. Black Widow and Bruce Banner stood over a computer whispering back and forth, and there were muted sounds of crashing and fighting through a door leading out of the main room. 

“Who the hell are you?” Black Widow asked, looking up from the computer. 

“Language.” Hawkeye said, appearing behind the others. “But who are you?”

summary:
HEROES CALL MARVEL # 9 - YOUNG MARVELMAN
Of course with no new issues of Captain Marvel available to republish, there were no...
body:
HEROES CALL MARVEL # 9 - YOUNG MARVELMAN

Of course with no new issues of Captain Marvel available to republish, there were no issues of Captain Marvel Jr. to republish. Mick Anglo created Young Marvelman. He first appeared in Young Marvelman #25, February 1954 (UK) and continued through issue #370.

His alter ego was Dickie Dauntless, a telegraph messenger. He transformed into his super-hero identity by crying out the name of his mentor, “Marvelman”.

summary: Okay so Captain Marvel is one of those highly enjoyable movies that I'm never going to see again, but it was worth the price of...
body:
Okay so Captain Marvel is one of those highly enjoyable movies that I’m never going to see again, but it was worth the price of admission for two reasons:

1) The cat

2) The cinematic masterpiece of a moment when Carol beats up bad guys to the sound of ‘I’m just a girl’
